data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to resolve to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees **cannot represent span-based methods**, so compilation may succeed but the compiled expression throws at runtime (especially with `preferInterpretation: true`).

## Fix

Force the call to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects **`.Reverse()`** on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` version returning `void`). Use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` or `.AsEnumerable().Reverse()` for those cases.
